Solvent extraction (industry-standard) is the technology studied in this paper; the authors frame solvent extraction as the most successful industrial process for REE separation.,D2EHPA and Cyanex272 were the extractants evaluated; kerosene was used as the diluent; HNO3 and NaOH were used to adjust aqueous pH.,"La, Nd, Dy, and Gd were the target rare earth metals tested.",Not mentioned in source.,Extraction efficiencies reported: Dy ~100% (with D2EHPA and with the 8:2 Cyanex272:D2EHPA mixture); Gd ~100% with D2EHPA under optimal conditions; Nd extraction efficiency ranged ~26.47% (mixture) to lower values with other extractants; La extraction efficiency ~30% with D2EHPA and ~29% with Cyanex272.,"Reported separation factors: mixture (8 mL Cyanex272 + 2 mL D2EHPA) Dy/Nd = 3640.27 and Dy/Gd = 720.05; D2EHPA Dy/La = 4267.67, La/Gd = 243.91, Gd/Nd = 31.78, Nd/La = 7.67; Cyanex272 showed the lowest separation factors overall.",Contact time used in experiments: 10 min per extraction step; stirring at 450 rpm at room temperature (298–299 K).,Extractant concentrations tested: 0.05 M identified as optimal; phase ratio A:O = 1:1 using 10 mL organic per 10 mL aqueous in batch tests. No mass-based reagent consumption or cost per kg REE reported.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Laboratory-scale batch experiments (100 mL glassware; 10 mL phases); TRL: lab-scale (bench).,Not mentioned in source.
