Solvent extraction (SX) using D2EHPA as extractant.,D2EHPA extractant was used; reported recoveries: 99.5% Sm to organic phase and 80% Nd remaining in aqueous phase in a seven-stage process at A/O = 0.30.,"Light REEs: La, Ce, Pr, Nd; Medium: Sm, Eu, Gd; Heavy: Tb-Lu and Y. Performance specifically reported for Sm and Nd.",Not mentioned in source.,"99.5% Sm recovery to organic phase; 80% Nd recovery to aqueous phase in a seven-stage process at A/O = 0.30, validated at mini-pilot scale.",Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Mini-pilot scale continuous trials performed; TRL likely pilot demonstration (validated continuous trial).,Not mentioned in source.
"Solvent extraction and extraction chromatography (a solid-phase/extraction chromatography approach) were the primary technologies investigated in this paper; solvent extraction used D2EHPA in kerosene, and extraction chromatography used D2EHPA-impregnated C18 column material for REE fractionation.",Primary extractant: D2EHPA (97%) in kerosene for solvent extraction and D2EHPA impregnated on C18 for extraction chromatography. Stripping reagents: H2SO4 (1.25–2.5 M used; up to 2.5 M for improved Dy stripping) and oxalic acid (1 M used for Fe/B scrubbing). pH control with NH3OH and H2SO4; leach used CuSO4-based cementation and small H2SO4 addition to PLS.,"Target metals: Nd, Pr, Sm, Dy (primary focus); Co, Fe, B monitored as impurities.",Real NdFeB magnet waste leachate (PLS) produced by a cementation CuSO4-based leach; tests used both this real PLS and synthetic sulfate solutions mimicking loaded strip compositions.,"Solvent extraction (3 counter-current stages, 35 vol.% D2EHPA, O/A 1.5): Nd 99.9%, Dy 99.7%, Pr 92%, Sm 91.2% extracted. Stripping: Nd >80% with 1.25 M H2SO4 (A/O 0.5); Dy stripping >85% with 2.5 M H2SO4 (A/O 3) or >70% with three counter-current stages. Fe and Co remained under ~10% during stripping; oxalic acid scrubbing removed >86% Fe and >88% B in one stage.","Quantitative separation factors not reported. However, extraction and chromatographic fractionation produced clear separations: Co and impurities elute before REEs; Nd/Pr co-elute in one fraction with combined purity >98% (after chromatography), Pr partial recovery >50% in separate fraction; Dy elutes later at higher acid strengths (≥0.9–1.18 M H2SO4) indicating good HREE/LREE separation. No numeric separation factor values provided in source.",Leaching: 25 min cementation leach. Liquid-liquid stripping/scrubbing contact times ~10 min (batch lab tests). Chromatography: 50 µL injections at 1 mL/min eluate flow; fractions collected every 30 s. Equilibrium for solvent extraction achieved within four counter-current stages at pH ~1.8 (lab-scale).,Specific reagent consumption rates (kg reagent per kg REE) not provided. Reported concentrations/loads: 35 vol.% D2EHPA in organic phase; D2EHPA impregnation measured as 0.930 mmol loaded on lab chromatography column. Leach uses 356 g CuSO4·5H2O per L lixiviant and small H2SO4 addition to PLS. No mass-based reagent consumption per kg REE reported.,Not mentioned in source.,Purity: Nd+Pr fraction achieved combined purity >98% (after chromatographic separation); a Pr fraction >75% purity was observed for one fraction; Sm and Dy were recoverable in separate fractions at specified eluate concentrations. Oxalate precipitation yields near-complete REE recovery but does not separate individual REEs.,Lab-scale demonstration: bench solvent extraction in 250 mL beakers and lab HPLC-scale extraction chromatography using a 4.6×150 mm D2EHPA-impregnated column. Authors position approach as scalable and industrially relevant but provide no pilot/commercial TRL; TRL likely lab/pilot (TRL 3-4) based on presented experiments.,Not mentioned in source. No cost or USD/kg REE figures reported; authors state data available on request.
Solvent extraction (split-anion approach using ionic liquids combined with neutral extractants),"Ionic liquids: trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium thiocyanate or nitrate ([C101][SCN], [C101][NO3]); Neutral extractants: Cyanex 923, TBP; Stripping/scrubbing agents: water, CaCl2 (1.0 M), oxalic acid for precipitation",Neodymium (Nd(III)) and Dysprosium (Dy(III)),"Synthetic chloride solutions mimicking NdFeB magnet composition (64 g L-1 Nd, 14 g L-1 Dy); real magnet waste or impurity-containing streams not tested in this study","Reported extraction/stripping efficiencies: Nd stripping up to 99.6% (for [C101][NO3] aqueous contact). Example low extraction: Cyanex 923 in toluene gave 6.4% Dy, 0.5% Nd extraction (not optimized). General batch/continuous extraction percent E and distribution ratios reported in tables (specific values not quoted here) and recycling showed no loss after 3 cycles.",Separation factors reported: up to a = 8.3 with 40 wt% Cyanex 923 in [C101][SCN]; up to a = 9.7 using 2.5 M CaCl2 as aqueous modifier; undiluted [A336][NO3] gave best separation factors in nitrate systems,"Equilibrium in batch tests ~20 minutes. In continuous mixer-settler demonstration, extraction and stripping runs equilibrated over longer durations (10 h extraction, 16 h stripping for the experiments reported).",Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Purity metrics not directly reported as % REE purity. Authors note co-extraction of Nd requiring scrubbing to improve Dy purity; Nd stripping efficiency up to 99.6% reported for Nd recovery from ionic liquid.,"Lab-to-bench continuous demo: mixer-settler units (mixers 0.12 L, settlers 0.48 L); TRL: bench-scale continuous demonstration (approx. TRL 4-5). Full plant flowsheet not tested",Not mentioned in source.
Solvent extraction (liquid-liquid extraction) using D2EHPA diluted in kerosene was studied; feed was Nd and Y in 1 M HNO3.,D2EHPA (di-2-ethyl-hexyl-phosphate) 0.30 M in kerosene as organic phase; aqueous feed in 1 M HNO3.,Neodymium (Nd) and Yttrium (Y).,Not mentioned in source.,Y extraction efficiency: 93%. Nd extraction efficiency: Not mentioned in source.,Successful separation of Y from Nd was reported using 0.30 M D2EHPA; quantitative separation factors not provided in source.,Mixing/contact time: 25 minutes (mechanical shaking). Additional processing time for phase separation not specified.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,"Laboratory-scale experimental study (equilibrium experiments); TRL: lab research (TRL 1-3) implied, no pilot/commercial scale reported.",Not mentioned in source.
Solvent extraction (magnetic-assisted solvent extraction) using PC88A (HEHEHP) in paraffin oil; study focuses on Dy(III) and other RE(III)s using a Dy(III)-PC88A-HCl system,"PC88A (mono-2-ethylhexyl phosphonate, HEHEHP) in paraffin oil as extractant; aqueous phase: DyCl3 in 0.1 M HCl. Ligand concentrations varied 0.25–1 M (PC88A) and experiments up to 2 M for some REs","Dysprosium (Dy(III)) primarily; also tested Sm(III), Ho(III), Er(III) — generalizable to heavy REs",Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned quantitatively in source; authors state separation factors need to be quantified in future work and hypothesize improved selectivity for more magnetic REs but no numerical separation factors provided,Kinetic observations reported: transient dynamics with symmetry breaking over ~80 s and quasi-steady state by ~160 s in lab-scale droplet experiments; no full process throughput times or stage counts provided,"Not reported as per mass or kg/kg REE; only extractant concentrations used in experiments (0.25–1 M, up to 2 M for some heavy RE tests) are provided",Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,"Lab-scale (Hele-Shaw cell cuvettes, single organic droplets ~4–5 mm diameter); TRL: laboratory proof-of-concept; no pilot/commercial scale reported",Not mentioned in source.
Non-aqueous solvent extraction (NASX) using neutral extractant P350.,Extractant: P350 at 0.2 mol/L; solvent phase uses PEG 200 (70 vol%); stripping reagents: 0.04 mol/L HCl for Nd and 0.4 mol/L HCl for Dy.,Nd(III) and Dy(III).,"Simulated NdFeB magnetic immersion/leach solution (laboratory simulation), not reported as real industrial waste stream testing.",Extraction: Dy(III) extraction efficiency up to 85% with only ~6% co-extraction of Nd(III). Stripping: 97.11% Nd and 98.5% Dy recovered from loaded organic phase by sequential HCl stripping.,Reported separation factors: βNd/Dy = 201 under 70 vol% PEG200 with 0.2 M P350; in simulated immersion solution βDy/Nd = 83.4 (high selectivity).,Equilibration time investigated but specific equilibration time not provided in summary; process design indicates 3 counter-current SX stages required to completely extract Dy(III).,"Concentrations of extractant and strip reagents reported (0.2 M P350; 0.04 M and 0.4 M HCl), but no mass-based reagent consumption or kg/kg REE data provided.",Not mentioned in source.,"High selectivity with low co-extraction suggests high purity streams: Dy extracted with 85% and only 6% Nd co-extraction in simulation; sequential stripping recovered >97% of each element, indicating potential for high-purity separated streams though exact final product purities not quantified.",Laboratory-scale study with proposed process; TRL not stated and no pilot/commercial scale demonstrated in the source.,"Authors claim the approach could be a 'low-cost alternative', but no quantitative cost data (USD/kg REE) or cost analysis provided."
