Solvent extraction and organic ligand-based selective precipitation are discussed as incumbent chemical methods; the paper's demonstrated technology is a precipitation-based laminar co-flow (LCM) aqueous selective precipitation method for Nd/Dy separation.,"Sodium dibutyl phosphate (NaDBP), prepared from dibutyl phosphate (HDBP) and NaOH, is the reactant/extractant used for selective precipitation in aqueous solution.",Neodymium (Nd) and Dysprosium (Dy) are the target metals investigated in this study.,"Not tested on actual magnet waste in this study; experiments used aqueous solutions of NdCl3 and DyCl3 as model feeds, with applicability to NdFeB leachates suggested but not demonstrated.",Dy purity in precipitate: up to 99.9% for 50:50 and 30:70 Nd:Dy feeds; 100% from one column at 21 h; for 20% Dy feed LCM achieved 95.8% in 4 h and 97.6% in 30 h. LCM reaches 95% Dy purity in 4 h vs 30 h for bulk mixing (BMM).,Not mentioned in source.,Processing times reported: experiments used injection times from 45 min to 30 h; key benchmarks: 95% Dy purity achieved in 4 h (LCM) vs 30 h (BMM); 100% purity achieved in one column at 21 h.,NaDBP used at concentrations ranging from 1.2 mM to 120 mM in experiments; selective precipitation experiments used 1.2 mM NaDBP with 4 mM NdCl3 and varying DyCl3. No mass or reagent consumption per kg REE or costs provided.,Not mentioned in source.,Dy purity up to 99.9% (50:50 and 30:70 feeds) and 100% in a column after 21 h; 95.8% achieved from 20% Dy feed in 4 h.,"Lab-scale microfluidic devices with channel volumes 0.02–0.49 mL; experiments increased output (e.g., 0.76 mg dried sample in LCM for 4 h, 20% Dy feed). TRL: lab-scale, not demonstrated on real feedstocks; scalability not yet established.",Not mentioned in source.
