Solvent-based leaching using a deep eutectic solvent (DES: TEAC-LA) for selective leaching of REEs from NdFeB waste (solvent extraction/leaching category),TEAC-LA (tetraethylammonium chloride + levulinic acid) deep eutectic solvent; Nd2O3 solubility >75.6 g/L in the DES,Neodymium (Nd) is the primary target; Fe is present in low leaching (<0.435%) indicating selectivity for REEs and product purified to Nd2O3 (99.649%),NdFeB waste (magnet waste),Nd leaching ratio up to 97.63%,Separation factor (REE vs Fe) can exceed 9000; Fe co-leaching <0.435% supporting very high selectivity,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,No explicit energy consumption data provided; thermal stability up to 132.4 °C and working viscosity 12.8 cP are reported but energy per kg REE is not mentioned,Nd2O3 purity 99.649%,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.
Solvent extraction (liquid-liquid) using an undiluted non-fluorinated ionic liquid (trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium nitrate) applied to iron-free nitric acid leachates from roasted NdFeB magnets; also includes scrubbing/stripping and precipitation steps to produce oxides,Trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium nitrate ionic liquid as extractant; ammonia nitrate (NH4NO3) as salting-out complexing agent; Na2EDTA for selective stripping of Dy; oxalic acid for precipitation; HNO3 for leaching,"Neodymium (Nd), Dysprosium (Dy) and Cobalt (Co) targeted",Iron-free nitric acid leachates from roasted NdFeB magnets; experiments also performed on synthetic solutions mimicking roasted magnet leachates,"Extraction efficiencies reported: Nd 80.5% and Dy 76.4% at very high feed concentrations; when diluted 2x: Dy 96.9% and Nd 94.6%. Back-extraction (scrubbing) left Nd and Dy at 0.38% and 0.35% in organic phase under optimum scrubbing. Selective EDTA stripping of Dy achieved 58.9% (single step) and up to ~79.8% at 70°C; Nd stripping low (~2.3–4.0%) during selective stripping. Final oxide purities: CoO 99.8% (yield 99.4%), Nd2O3 99.6% (yield 99.3%), Dy2O3 99.8% (yield 99.1%)",Separation factors reported: alpha_Nd/Co = 590 and alpha_Dy/Co = 500 (for diluted synthetic feed),"Extraction: 60 min at 60–70°C (optimal 60–70°C, 1900 rpm). Scrubbing: 90 min at 80°C. Selective EDTA stripping: 30–60 min (30 min sufficient for EDTA complexation; 1 h used in some stripping steps)","Reagent specifics: 10 M NH4NO3 used for extraction/scrubbing; Na2EDTA 0.03 M for selective Dy stripping; oxalic acid stoichiometric amounts for precipitation; ionic liquid loading examples: organic phase containing ~58.1 g/L Nd and 5.5 g/L Dy; feed concentrations up to ~248.5 g/L Nd, 21.4 g/L Dy in synthetic solution. No mass-based reagent consumption per kg REE or cost data reported in source.",Not mentioned in source.,"Final oxide purities: Nd2O3 99.6%, Dy2O3 99.8%, CoO 99.8% as measured by TXRF","Laboratory-scale experiments (4 mL vials, bench-top shaker). Recycling tested for at least three cycles. TRL: lab-scale / bench demonstration. No pilot/commercial scale reported","No explicit cost or USD/kg REE figures provided. Authors note phosphonium nitrate ionic liquids are relatively inexpensive and produced at large scale, but no quantitative cost data disclosed in source."
Solvent extraction (D2EHPA-based) applied to sulfuric leachate from NdFeB magnet waste; primary technology studied in this paper.,"D2EHPA (0.3, 0.6, 0.9, 1.2 M) in various diluents (Solvent 70, hexane, octane, toluene, cyclohexanone, chloroform, 1-octanol); stripping reagent: HCl (0.5–3 M).","Nd, Dy, Pr, Gd primarily; Co and B measured as contaminants but not extracted significantly.",Real magnet waste: sulfuric acid leachate from selectively roasted NdFeB magnet scrap (real leachate).,Extraction to organic phase: 100% transfer of REEs at 0.9–1.2 M D2EHPA in hexane/octane. Stripping: 100% at ≥2 M HCl.,Separation factors: highest Dy/Nd achieved with 0.3 M D2EHPA in hexane (specific numerical factors reported in Table 2 in paper; qualitatively ~99% HREE vs ~50% LREE extraction under those conditions). Typical adjacent-REE separation factor with D2EHPA ~2.5 reported in literature.,"Extraction kinetics: equilibrium reached within ~3 min (most diluents) or ~5 min (cyclohexanone, 1-octanol) in 3.5 mL batch tests; stripping contact performed for 5 min.",Reagent concentrations reported: D2EHPA at 0.3–1.2 M in diluents; HCl for stripping 0.5–3 M. Paper does not report reagent consumption per kg REE or stage-wise reagent mass usage (Not mentioned in source)..,Not mentioned in source.,"Paper cites that solvent extraction can achieve up to 99.99% purity (general literature), but does not report final product purity achieved from these specific experiments (Not mentioned in source for experimental purity).",Scale/TRL: laboratory bench-scale batch experiments in 3.5 mL vials; TRL ~3 (lab-scale). No pilot/commercial deployment reported.,Not mentioned in source.
"Precipitation-based lanthanide separation using macrocyclic DO3A-type chelators (aqueous selective precipitation). Comparable to solvent extraction in selectivity but aqueous, scalable; technology type: precipitation-based chelation separations.","Macrocyclic DO3A-type chelators (e.g., L3) as primary reagent; coordinating additives such as acetate, α-HIBA, glycolate, lactate used to tune separations; digestion used 65% HNO3 and ammonium oxalate for oxalate precipitation of Lns.","Target metals: lanthanides present in NdFeB magnets—primarily Nd, Pr, Dy, Tb, Ho (also Sm not specifically highlighted); focus on Nd/Dy, Pr/Nd, Tb/Dy, Tb/Ho separations.","Feedstock tested: NdFeB magnet material from electric car motors (digested in 65% HNO3 to produce Ln chloride feed); not tested on leachates like grinding coolant or electroplating effluent—i.e., solid magnet scrap processed to chloride/oxalate intermediates.",67% recovery of Nd in the demonstrated case study; purity of Nd product reached 99.7% after five rounds of precipitation.,"Nd/Dy separation factor approximately 40 achievable in single round under optimized additive conditions (e.g., α-HIBA or acetate); single-round SFs comparable to industrial solvent extraction.","Kinetics: some chelates (L3) achieve 90% precipitation within 15 minutes; effective separations (e.g., Nd/Dy SF≈42) achieved within ~3 hours; reactions typically stirred overnight for some experiments but key separations occur within hours.",Reagent consumption: chelator L3 used stoichiometrically with Ln3+ (1:1) in reprecipitations (no replenishment required); coordinating additives used in multiple equivalents—acetate optimal at ~10 equivalents; α-HIBA effective near stoichiometric ratios. Exact mass or kg/kg REE not provided in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Final Nd product purity achieved: 99.7% (case study after five rounds).,Scale/TRL: laboratory-scale demonstration including a case study processing a single automotive magnet; authors describe system as scalable but provide no pilot or commercial demonstration—TRL: lab-scale (approx. TRL 3-4). Specific volumes (mL/L) not provided in main text.,"No quantitative cost data or USD/kg REE provided. Authors note acetate is low-cost and chelator is recoverable (stoichiometric use, recovered via UF and oxalate precipitation), suggesting potential cost benefits, but no TEA numbers are given in source."
Ionic liquid-based thermomorphic leaching/extraction system (combined leaching and extraction),[Hbet][Tf2N] ionic liquid (betainium bis(trifluoromethylsulfonyl)imide); oxalic acid for stripping/precipitation; Na2SO4 for salting-out to recover ionic liquid; NaNO3 (1 M) as salting agent to improve Nd/Dy/Co transfer to aqueous phase; aqueous ammonia for cobalt removal; roasting (microwave or oven) as pre-treatment.,"Neodymium (Nd), Dysprosium (Dy), Cobalt (Co); iron (Fe) is matrix to separate from. Final products Nd2O3 and Dy2O3.",Roasted NdFeB magnet powders (lab-prepared from demagnetized NdFeB magnets); not industrial waste streams like grinding coolant or electroplating effluent—tested on roasted magnet scrap/powder.,Overall REE recovery >99% (authors report >99% recovery); oxalate stripping can achieve ~100% stripping of REE/Co from aqueous phase.,"High Nd/Fe and Dy/Fe separation factors reported qualitatively; specific numeric separation factor values are shown in figures (e.g., Fig. 15) but exact numeric values are Not mentioned in source text excerpt.","Leaching: 48-72 hours for complete REE leaching (dependent on particle size and conditions); Stripping (oxalic acid precipitation): ~10 minutes at room temperature; microwave roasting is faster than oven roasting (roasting oven: 950°C, 3–15 h).","Oxalic acid: stoichiometric amounts for stripping (i.e., ~1:1 equivalents to REE/Co to precipitate as oxalates); NaNO3 used at 1 M in aqueous phase to enhance distribution; Na2SO4 used for salting-out (quantity to reduce ionic liquid loss to <0.15 wt% — reported at 3 M Na2SO4 tests). No mass-specific reagent consumption (kg/kg REE) reported in text.",Not mentioned in source.,REE product purity >99.9 wt% (final oxides after calcination reported >99.9%).,Lab-scale proof-of-concept (batch experiments in 4 mL vials; roasted magnet powders). TRL: lab-scale (likely TRL 3-4). No pilot or industrial demonstration reported in source.,Not mentioned in source.
Solvent extraction and extraction chromatography (solid-phase extraction chromatography) were the primary technologies investigated in this study.,Primary extractant: D2EHPA (97%) in kerosene for solvent extraction and impregnation of chromatographic column; strip reagents: H2SO4 (1.25–2.5 M used for stripping and gradient elution) and oxalic acid (1 M used for scrubbing Fe and B). Lixiviant for cementation leach: CuSO4-based solution (356 g CuSO4·5H2O per L) with 25 min leach time.,"Nd, Pr, Sm, Dy (primary targets).",Real NdFeB magnet waste leachate (pregnant leach solution produced by a cementation leach of ground NdFeB scrap; PLS contains ~62.9 g/L Fe and 20.5 g/L Nd in reported average).,"Solvent extraction: three counter-current stages with 35 vol.% D2EHPA and O/A 1.5 achieved 99.9% Nd, 99.7% Dy, 92% Pr, 91.2% Sm extraction. Stripping: >80% Nd stripping with 1.25 M H2SO4 at A/O 0.5; Dy stripping improved to >85% with 2.5 M H2SO4 A/O 3 or >70% with three counter-current stages. Chromatography fractions: >50% Pr in one fraction, remaining Pr recovered with >92% Nd; combined Nd+Pr purity >98%.","Specific numerical separation factors not provided. Reported performance: chromatographic gradient elution enabled separation of Nd/Pr from Sm and Dy into distinct fractions; Sm elutes at >0.4 M H2SO4 and Dy at >0.9 M H2SO4. Co-extraction of impurities limited (Fe 7%, B 4%, Co 2%) under optimized solvent-extraction conditions. No explicit separation factor ratios (e.g., Nd/Fe) reported in source.","Leaching: 25 min cementation leach. Solvent extraction/stripping: lab-scale mixing with 10 min contact for stripping/scrubbing stages. Chromatography: 50 µL injections at 1 mL/min eluate, fractions collected every 30 s. No overall plant throughput or continuous processing time reported.",Specific reagent consumption metrics per kg REE not provided. Reported reagent usages: organic phase containing 35 vol.% D2EHPA; column impregnation loaded 0.930 mmol D2EHPA; stripping used 1.25–2.5 M H2SO4 and 1 M oxalic acid for scrubbing. No mass-based reagent consumption (kg reagent/kg REE) reported in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Chromatography achieved combined Nd+Pr purity >98% in one fraction; one Pr fraction purity >75%; chromatographic separation can ensure Sm content below 0.01% in Nd fraction. No final oxide purity numbers reported post-precipitation/calcinaton.,Lab-scale experiments: solvent-extraction in 250 mL beakers and small-scale chromatographic columns with 50 µL injections. TRL: lab-scale (likely TRL 3-4). No pilot or commercial deployment reported.,Not mentioned in source.
Solvent extraction (using ionic liquid [A336][SCN] and organophosphorous extractants Cyanex 923 and D2EHPA) and acid leaching with deep-eutectic solvent (DES choline chloride:lactic acid) were used to dissolve and separate REEs from NdFeB magnets,"DES: choline chloride:lactic acid (1:2) for leaching; Extractants: [A336][SCN] (Aliquat 336 thiocyanate) 0.9 M in toluene for Fe/Co/B removal; Cyanex 923 0.9 M in toluene and D2EHPA 0.9 M in toluene tested for Nd/Dy separation. Stripping reagents: HCl (B), EDTA (Fe, Co), water (Dy), oxalic acid (Nd precipitation)","Nd, Dy, Fe, Co, B targeted; final oxides Nd2O3 and Dy2O3 recovered",Roasted and non-roasted NdFeB magnet powders (lab-scale prepared leachates from actual magnet samples) were tested; leaching in DES at 70°C (typically 12–24 h),"Specific overall recovery % values for each metal are not reported explicitly for leaching/extraction in the source; Nd and Dy oxide purities reported: Nd2O3 99.87%, Dy2O3 99.94%",Separation factors (Dy/Nd and REE/Fe etc.) are reported in tables in the paper but specific numeric SFs are not quoted in the provided text. Paper states D2EHPA gives higher D but similar SF to Cyanex 923; overall DES-based extraction yields higher SFs than aqueous systems,Leaching: typically 12–24 h at 70°C. Solvent extraction: equilibration times 5–20 min (20 min used for many batch tests; 15 min chosen for Nd/Dy extraction). Stripping: 60 min typical; precipitation/oxalate precipitation ~25–30 min,"Concentrations used: 0.9 M extractants ([A336][SCN], Cyanex 923, D2EHPA in toluene); stoichiometric oxalic acid for Nd precipitation. No explicit reagent mass per kg REE or consumption cost data reported",Not mentioned in source.,Nd2O3 purity 99.87%; Dy2O3 purity 99.94% after precipitation and calcination,"Bench-scale pilot demonstration using mixer-settlers (5 stages, 120 mL units), demonstrating scale-up feasibility; TRL ~4–5 (lab to bench-scale demonstrated)",Not mentioned in source.
"Acid leaching (HCl, HNO3) followed by solvent extraction using an ionic liquid (trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium chloride) and oxalate precipitation.","HCl, HNO3 for leaching; trihexyl(tetradecyl)phosphonium chloride (Cyphos IL 101) as solvent extraction ionic liquid; oxalic acid for precipitation. NH4Cl or CaCl2 used as salting-out/ matrix; water, air; minimal other chemicals.","Nd and Dy (primary), also Pr included in Ln sum; Co and Fe considered as impurities to separate.",Not mentioned in source.,Leaching: Nd and Dy >90% under sufficient acid equivalents (n(HCl)/n(Ln) ≥ ~3.5). Precipitation: Nd precipitation ~100% at n(oxalic)/n(Nd)=1.5 in absence of HCl. Losses: ~0.13 g/L Nd and 0.10 g/L Dy lost to IL extraction in reported batch.,"Separation factor Co/Dy ~20,000 (no HCl) increasing to ~130,000 at 1 M HCl for Cyphos IL101 extraction conditions tested; rare-earths not extracted while Co,C u, Mn are extracted strongly.",Roasting: up to 15 h at 950°C for full oxidation; Leaching: typically 15 h at 80°C (or up to days at 100°C for larger scale) to reach equilibrium; Solvent extraction: 1 h at 60°C; Precipitation: 2 h at RT.,Leaching: n(HCl)/n(Ln) optimal ~3.5 (acid equivalents); roasting reduces acid consumption by ~4 molar equivalents vs non-roasted. Oxalic acid consumption: 1.5 molar equivalents per REE atom. Other reagent losses minimal; IL losses <100 ppm solubility; NH4Cl used at 3.5 M as salting agent.,Not mentioned in source.,Leachate purity (REEs): ≥90 wt% (Nd+Dy+Pr) at n(HCl)/n(Ln)=3.5. Final product: rare-earth oxides produced via oxalate precipitation and calcination (implied high purity suitable for magnet feedstock).,"Lab-scale proof-of-principle (bench-scale batch experiments, grams to tens of grams); TRL ~3-4.",Not mentioned in source.
