Solvent extraction (using Primene 81R·Cyanex 572 ionic liquid and Cyanex 272/Cyanex 572 as extractants),"Primene 81R·Cyanex 572 ionic liquid (P81R·Cy572) diluted in Solvesso 100; Cyanex 272 and Cyanex 572; DEHPA, EHEHPA mentioned as comparators; stripping agents HCl 1.2–4 M and citric acid 1 M; diluents: kerosene, toluene, cumene, Solvesso 100/200","Neodymium (Nd), Dysprosium (Dy), Terbium (Tb); broader context mentions Pr and Sm as REEs of interest","Synthetic magnet waste leachate formulated to match real NdFeB magnet waste concentrations (aqueous chloride medium, 4 M Cl-, Nd/Tb/Dy at specified g dm-3)",Nd recovery 99.99% (purity 99.7%); Tb elimination/removal 99.99%; Dy elimination 99% in two counter-current stages using 0.30 M P81R·Cy572 IL,Reported separation factor Dy/Nd up to 86 (using 0.30 M P81R and Cy572 equimolar IL); general statement of good Dy/Nd and Tb/Nd separation factors with Cy572 vs Cy272,Contact time to equilibrium: ~5 min (10 min used experimentally); counter-current process required 11 contacts to reach steady-state; McCabe-Thiele indicates at least 2 stages for Dy removal at A:O 1:4,Not mentioned in source.,Not mentioned in source.,Nd product purity reported as 99.7% after two-stage counter-current extraction with P81R·Cy572 IL,"Lab-scale bench experiments using separatory funnels (aqueous 5–20 mL contacts, repeated 11 times); synthetic leachate mimicking real waste. TRL: lab-scale (approx. TRL 3)",Not mentioned in source.
"Solvent extraction (nonaqueous/solvometallurgy) using Cyanex 923 with PEG 200 as the more-polar phase; the paper focuses on solvometallurgical solvent extraction rather than acid leaching, ion exchange, electrochemical, or membrane methods.",Cyanex 923 (trialkyl phosphine oxide mixture) as extractant in LP phase; PEG 200 (more-polar phase) as feed solvent; diluent GS190 (hydrocarbon) with 10 vol% 1-decanol modifier; stripping with aqueous oxalic acid. Also studied LiCl and HCl as chloride sources and small water additions in PEG 200.,Neodymium (Nd(III)) and Dysprosium (Dy(III)) are the target metals.,Simulated NdFeB magnet leachate prepared from rare-earth oxides (synthetic feed mimicking pregnant leach solutions); no tests on real industrial magnet waste streams reported in this paper.,"Dy extraction: ~71–72% extracted per extraction stage under optimized conditions; Nd coextraction low (~5–6%). Stripping (oxalic acid) achieved >99.9% (all cycles) and >99.99% in specific test, producing Dy oxalate precipitate.","Reported Nd/Dy separation factors vary with conditions: 69 (PEG200+30-40% water, LiCl), 54 (PEG200+30-40% water, HCl), ~260 (2 M HCl, 30% water), up to >6000 at 0.5 M Cyanex 923 under optimized HCl conditions; under simulated NdFeB oxide feed conditions, separation factor ~42 with 72% Dy extraction.",Extraction equilibrium reached in 60 min (1 hour) under lab mixing conditions; stripping contact time 60 min (1 hour). McCabe-Thiele analysis indicates at least 3 extraction stages required for complete Dy removal.,Extractant concentration example: 0.5 mol L-1 Cyanex 923 in LP phase with 10 vol% 1-decanol in GS190. Oxalic acid used at stoichiometric amount for stripping (specific mmol/L given for 0.9 g/L Dy: 8.3 mmol L-1). No mass-based reagent consumption or USD/kg REE cost data reported.,Not mentioned in source.,"Stripping produced Dy oxalate precipitate and stripping efficiencies >99.9–99.99%; authors state oxalate can be calcined to produce pure Dy2O3, implying high purity product though quantitative purity % not provided.",Laboratory bench-scale experiments with synthetic/simulated feeds; TRL: lab-scale (no pilot/commercial demonstration reported). Authors present McCabe-Thiele analysis and conceptual flow sheet suggesting potential industrial scale-up (3 extraction stages + scrubbing + stripping) but no pilot data.,"Not mentioned in source. (No specific reagent cost, USD/kg REE, or operating cost data provided; only qualitative comment that chloride salts are cheaper)."
Solvent extraction using ionic liquid ([P66614][Cy272]) as task-specific ionic liquid; also acid leaching (HCl) prior to extraction,Leaching reagent: HCl (2-3 mol L^-1). Extractant: [P66614][Cy272] ionic liquid (0.01 mol L^-1 used for Fe removal and REE separation). Cyanex 272 and Cyphos IL 101 used in synthesis; stripping with 0.5 mol L^-1 HNO3. NaOH used for iron precipitation and Na2CO3 used to regenerate IL,"Dy, Pr, Nd primarily; Fe and B also targeted (Fe selectively removed)",Real magnet manufacturing waste: leach liquor from waste NdFeB magnets recovered from end-of-life HDDs,"Iron removal: 100% extraction with ~4% co-extraction of REEs using 0.01 mol L^-1 IL. HCl recovery: up to 81.1% with 1 mol L^-1 IL. Leaching: near-complete leaching (100% at optimal conditions: 2 mol L^-1 HCl, 80°C, 90 min) for REEs, Fe, B. Post-extraction raffinate Dy at 6.0 mg L^-1 after two extraction stages at O/A 2:3",Separation factors reported: Dy/Pr = 18.55; Dy/Nd = 15.52 at pH 2.03,Leaching: 90 minutes at 80°C. Batch liquid-liquid extractions performed with 15 min contact; counter-current extraction required two stages at O/A 2:3 to achieve reported separation/enrichment,"Specific reagent consumption (kg/kg REE) not provided. Paper notes HCl concentration in leach liquor (~1.22 mol L^-1) and that IL enables HCl recovery (81.1%), reducing alkali consumption for neutralization but does not quantify reagent usage per kg REE",Not mentioned in source.,"Purity: After iron removal and precipitation, recovered Fe2O3 was free of REEs per SEM-EDS. REE purity numbers for final separated fractions not provided; however iron removal reduced REE co-contamination to ~4% during iron extraction step",Lab-scale experiments using HDD magnet samples; batch extractions in 10 mL phases and small-scale leaching (grams of magnet). TRL: laboratory research (TRL 1-3).,No quantitative cost data (USD/kg REE) provided. Authors state operational cost reductions due to HCl recovery and IL reuse but do not provide numerical cost figures
